1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:14,300
 - 1989. As the Iron Curtain fell, Eastern European countries quickly integrate into a globalizing

2
00:00:14,300 --> 00:00:22,460
 world economy. Within just three decades, Central, Eastern, and Southeastern European economies,

3
00:00:22,460 --> 00:00:28,920
 also called CESI countries, have doubled trade as a share of GDP. Foreign direct investment

4
00:00:28,920 --> 00:00:34,740
 into the region has increased seven-fold. Global supply chains have created more efficient

5
00:00:34,740 --> 00:00:41,500
 and specialized production by drawing on countries' relative strength. CESI countries have quickly

6
00:00:41,500 --> 00:00:48,560
 integrated into global supply chains. That means they are importing intermediate goods from elsewhere

7
00:00:48,560 --> 00:00:56,100
 and integrating these into the goods they are exporting. By 2018, a quarter of CESI exports

8
00:00:56,100 --> 00:01:03,380
 are imported inputs from other countries. And in turn, over half of CESI exports are used

9
00:01:03,380 --> 00:01:11,320
 as inputs for production by other countries. For example, European businesses have been outsourcing

10
00:01:11,320 --> 00:01:18,220
 or shifting production to CESI countries to take advantage of lower-cost skilled labor, including

11
00:01:18,220 --> 00:01:25,080
 the German, French, and Italian automobile industry, which outsources to the Czech Republic, Hungary,

12
00:01:25,080 --> 00:01:30,160
 Poland, Romania, and Slovakia.

13
00:01:30,160 --> 00:01:36,300
 These regional supply chains contribute to strong trade and foreign direct investment linkages between

14
00:01:36,300 --> 00:01:47,080
 advanced European countries and CESI. 61% of CESI exports go to advanced European countries, and another 13% to CESI countries.

15
00:01:47,080 --> 00:01:54,360
 For foreign direct investment, 86% comes from advanced European countries.

16
00:01:54,360 --> 00:02:03,720
 And with this integration come clear benefits: lower transaction costs, greater production efficiency,

17
00:02:03,720 --> 00:02:09,080
 faster technology diffusion, and faster cross-country convergence in living standards.

18
00:02:09,080 --> 00:02:16,520
 Living standards in CESI continue to rise closer to those in the advanced European countries.

19
00:02:16,520 --> 00:02:22,360
 Despite these gains, threats to globalization have begun to appear.

20
00:02:22,360 --> 00:02:28,360
 While globalization has helped to lift more than a billion people out of extreme poverty,

21
00:02:28,360 --> 00:02:35,640
 during the pandemic, those threats increased as shortages of intermediate inputs and labor, together with jammed logistical systems,

22
00:02:35,640 --> 00:02:48,920
 disrupted supply chains.

23
00:02:48,920 --> 00:02:54,920
 Motor vehicle manufacturers reported shortages of intermediate goods, which were still being felt at the end of 2022.

24
00:02:54,920 --> 00:03:04,200
 Suppliers' delivery times shot up sharply while they have since come down.

25
00:03:04,200 --> 00:03:12,200
 The specialization in supply chains, which fostered production efficiency, became a source of fragility.

26
00:03:12,200 --> 00:03:23,480
 The war and reduced gas deliveries by Russia led to major realignments in energy and agricultural commodity markets.

27
00:03:23,480 --> 00:03:32,760
 In particular, Europe quickly achieved a sharp reduction for natural gas imports through determined policy action.

28
00:03:32,760 --> 00:03:41,960
 Together, the pandemic, the war, and global geopolitical tensions have led to a greater number of protectionist measures.

29
00:03:41,960 --> 00:03:49,640
 High-tech sectors linked to national security or strategic competition are among the most affected.

30
00:03:49,640 --> 00:03:53,000
 Europe is no exception to these trends.

31
00:03:53,000 --> 00:03:58,920
 The EU has started limiting the entry of foreign firms while encouraging domestic production.

32
00:03:58,920 --> 00:04:03,320
 Especially in strategic sectors, such as semiconductors.

33
00:04:03,320 --> 00:04:07,000
 European exporters also face rising barriers.

34
00:04:07,000 --> 00:04:12,360
 For example, in the US, new green subsidies favor local production.

35
00:04:12,360 --> 00:04:16,600
 Such green subsidies can help achieve climate goals,

36
00:04:16,600 --> 00:04:20,920
 but can also distort investment decisions and global supply relationships.

37
00:04:20,920 --> 00:04:27,080
 In this changing landscape, firms are increasingly looking to relocate production

38
00:04:27,080 --> 00:04:31,960
 to make supply chains more resilient and less vulnerable to geopolitical tensions.

39
00:04:31,960 --> 00:04:42,200
 Words like re-shoring, near-shoring, and on-shoring increasingly appear in company earning calls and annual reports.

40
00:04:42,200 --> 00:04:49,080
 How would greater trade and FDI fragmentation, caused by increasing protectionist measures,

41
00:04:49,080 --> 00:04:53,320
 affect the economic prospects of CESI countries?

42
00:04:53,320 --> 00:04:55,400
 Will the region take a hit?

43
00:04:55,400 --> 00:05:00,520
 Or could it also benefit from possible realignments of supply chains?

44
00:05:01,320 --> 00:05:08,280
 And how can policies help enhance the resilience of, and benefits from, cross-border supply chains?

45
00:05:08,280 --> 00:05:18,840
 Okay, let me now invite my distinguished panelists to the stage.

46
00:05:18,840 --> 00:05:23,560
 Debora Revoltela, Chief Economist of European Investment Bank.

47
00:05:23,560 --> 00:05:33,800
 Vasil Hudak, Chairman of Investment Company Javanea.

48
00:05:37,880 --> 00:05:42,360
