00:45:53,640 --> 00:45:57,160
 I think it was already mentioned in the previous capital, in the previous, the previous panel,

395
00:45:57,160 --> 00:46:03,240
 that those companies which are successful and are able to, to, to start, but then when they get to

396
00:46:03,240 --> 00:46:09,880
 the level of so-called scale-ups and they need more equity for them to be able to grow and to compete

397
00:46:09,880 --> 00:46:16,600
 globally, because in that situation size matters, they are not able to find it in the region or in,

398
00:46:16,600 --> 00:46:23,000
 unfortunately, in Europe either. So they have to go to US for IPOs, for spec operations or whatever,

399
00:46:23,000 --> 00:46:29,880
 or they are bought by, by somebody from outside. So, so this part of innovation is, is critical. And a

400
00:46:29,880 --> 00:46:36,280
 second point I would like to make is that, and somebody mentioned that not mentioning Ukraine in

401
00:46:36,280 --> 00:46:43,160
 this context is a missed opportunity, and I agree. And Ukraine has a lot of talent in IT, a lot of

402
00:46:43,160 --> 00:46:50,440
 innovation. Actually, the war, however tragic it is, but we know that the war also helps to bring a lot of

403
00:46:50,440 --> 00:46:56,040
 of innovation, because for country people to be able to survive, you have to, you have to be innovative.

404
00:46:56,040 --> 00:47:03,800
 And Ukraine, and we see in our investment company, we actually have a venture fund where we invest into,

405
00:47:03,800 --> 00:47:10,280
 into interesting Ukrainian startups, for example, drone technologies, very interesting, very interesting

406
00:47:10,280 --> 00:47:16,040
 things which are coming out of Ukraine, also because of this very tragic and difficult situation. But

407
00:47:16,040 --> 00:47:23,960
 I think Europe should use it and create partnerships with Ukraine, also on the IT and kind of innovation

408
00:47:23,960 --> 00:47:32,920
 level. Okay. Mr. Hudak, if I'm not mistaken, you have a plane to catch. So we will excuse you.

409
00:47:32,920 --> 00:47:39,720
 Thank you very much for your time. It was a pleasure to have a conversation with you. And now I'm going to

410
00:47:39,720 --> 00:47:45,880
 turn to the audience. If there are questions for the, for our panelists, please just

411
00:47:45,880 --> 00:48:08,040
 raise your hand. Do I see any questions? No? Okay, please. There is a lady with a mic.

412
00:48:13,960 --> 00:48:21,880
 To break the ice again, then. No, it's a question for Joseph Francois. Regarding the,

413
00:48:21,880 --> 00:48:28,200
 so the impact of the green transition rate on competitiveness and supply chain activities and

414
00:48:28,200 --> 00:48:36,680
 location in Europe. So was your point that basically we mainly need the CBAM mechanism to apply to both

415
00:48:36,680 --> 00:48:42,280
 the direct and indirect carbon content of imports, right? So that you really affect all the supply chain

416
00:48:42,280 --> 00:48:48,600
 activities. Or did you have in mind something else? And second, is there something else? The fact that,

417
00:48:48,600 --> 00:48:54,840
 of course, the CBAM cannot address your competitiveness in third markets, right? Non-European markets. Thanks.

418
00:48:54,840 --> 00:49:04,360
 Okay. So I guess my answer is you need a different CBAM. The one is designed, there was a lot of attention

419
00:49:04,360 --> 00:49:10,680
 paid to it being GATT legal. I don't think that it actually will have the intended, intended effects.

420
00:49:10,680 --> 00:49:18,280
 It may have unintended effects. There's been a good bit of work recently, now that we have more data,

421
00:49:18,280 --> 00:49:24,680
 looking at how much carbon is in the things we buy, right? And in a sense, focusing on unembodied carbon

422
00:49:24,680 --> 00:49:32,200
 is probably the way to go. There is provisions in CBAM for sort of the carbon intensity on your immediate

423
00:49:32,200 --> 00:49:40,920
 supply chain for imports. I see CBAM as being partly necessary politically so that you don't lose

424
00:49:40,920 --> 00:49:45,880
 domestic support to raise the cost of carbon for certain domestic industries by protecting them from

425
00:49:45,880 --> 00:49:53,400
 direct imports. But it doesn't recognize that, again, downstream industries are going to be affected

426
00:49:53,400 --> 00:50:02,840
 generically by the higher costs, right? And so it's not that a system of carbon taxes is not the way to go,

427
00:50:02,840 --> 00:50:09,960
 but it needs to be more, I think, better thought out and comprehensive. You need to focus on embodied

428
00:50:09,960 --> 00:50:16,840
 carbon, not just of, say, steel directly, but if I buy a washing machine from Korea or something, how much

429
00:50:16,840 --> 00:50:23,720
 carbon is in the steel if it's in that washing machine? But that means, in a sense,

430
00:50:23,720 --> 00:50:29,400
 we need a framework, as was mentioned earlier, to think about how we measure carbon in stuff

431
00:50:29,400 --> 00:50:38,920
 that enters the block. So I do think that's eventually where we're going. And if that's where we're going,

432
00:50:38,920 --> 00:50:45,080
 then if you have invested in having a greener grid, then that means that down the supply chain also

433
00:50:45,080 --> 00:50:52,840
 things are greener than they are from elsewhere. I'm just not convinced that the CBAM as it's set up

434
00:50:52,840 --> 00:51:01,240
 is going to do what the intentions are. So I guess the short answer is a different CBAM would probably work,

435
00:51:01,240 --> 00:51:05,720
 but not this one.

436
00:51:05,720 --> 00:51:07,240
 Okay. Any more questions? Or is the lady over there?

437
00:51:07,240 --> 00:51:14,520
 Thank you. Well, we heard from Mr. Hudak, but we had heard it already before,

438
00:51:14,520 --> 00:51:24,520
 that EU is good as the preceding finance and the seeding finance, so to say, but not then in the upscaling,

439
00:51:24,520 --> 00:51:29,400
 and which is really making the difference. So this question is for Ms. Revoltella to ask,

440
00:51:29,400 --> 00:51:35,000
 what is the reason? And is there something we can do about it to actually allow for these SMEs to do

441
00:51:35,000 --> 00:51:40,840
 the next step and then position themselves? Because indeed, when we look now, for instance,

442
00:51:40,840 --> 00:51:48,200
 when we are trying to favor net zero technologies manufacturing in Europe and we are creating the conditions

443
00:51:48,200 --> 00:51:56,120
 through public procurement, but then we will need companies who have the capacity to respond to such

444
00:51:56,120 --> 00:51:59,960
 public cause. So what can be done about it? Thank you.

445
00:51:59,960 --> 00:52:10,600
 Then I think I very much share the issue of the scaling up of firms and the

446
00:52:10,600 --> 00:52:17,400
 concern that we have at the European level. And as the EIB, we are quite active in trying to

447
00:52:17,400 --> 00:52:24,360
 support the growth of firms and particularly, we are particularly looking at the moment in which

448
00:52:24,360 --> 00:52:34,440
 from the innovation side, you transform and grow and also the first of a kind, if you want, a project

449
00:52:34,440 --> 00:52:40,360
 in terms of manufacturing. So we are trying to look at the whole spectrum in terms of

450
00:52:40,360 --> 00:52:47,160
 policy support. And I think it's quite important to think in this way. So, I always come

451
00:52:47,160 --> 00:52:56,120
 as an economist, what you have in this case is a sum up of multiple, if you want, market failures,

452
00:52:56,120 --> 00:53:05,880
 and then you need to have multiple responses. On the one side that we have on the green transition side,

453
00:53:05,880 --> 00:53:12,680
 you have one of the market failures is the carbon pricing that is still not fully internalized.

454
00:53:12,680 --> 00:53:18,920
 So you have as an answer, you have the carbon pricing is coming one, but then you need also to subsidize

455
00:53:18,920 --> 00:53:26,680
 the innovation side because we have other market failures exactly in the innovation side. So, you

456
00:53:26,680 --> 00:53:31,480
 have to sum up instruments and I think the combination of the two can be important. As an

457
00:53:31,480 --> 00:53:40,520
 institution, I was saying we are active both on the venture capital side. We have also product of

458
00:53:40,520 --> 00:53:47,480
 venture debt that are actually quite useful in the scaling up of innovation in the last phase of the

459
00:53:47,480 --> 00:53:56,280
 and innovation after the firms as the first rise of capital and before preparing for the second one.

460
00:53:56,280 --> 00:54:03,240
 We have an assessment of the product that we actually did, really looking at what is the effect on the

461
00:54:03,240 --> 00:54:10,040
 and the firms that received this kind of financing versus other firms that didn't receive and

462
00:54:10,040 --> 00:54:18,840
 were ex-ante identical. And we really see that the firms that receive the venture debt, actually they grow

463
00:54:18,840 --> 00:54:30,040
 faster and the reason is that actually they receive in the years after much better financing, additional financing.

464
00:54:30,040 --> 00:54:38,200
 So they just become stronger firms because they have an investor like us that actually give two things.

465
00:54:38,200 --> 00:54:45,560
 It gives this venture debt product but also a stamp of quality on the technologies, perceived positive in the market.

466
00:54:45,560 --> 00:54:57,160
 So it's much easier later for the firm to raise a better capital later. And I think somehow institutions like us can play this

467
00:54:57,160 --> 00:55:10,120
 role and particularly new technologies, an assessment of the technology providing a good financing but also providing a kind of an assessment that the business, the technology is

468
00:55:10,120 --> 00:55:15,720
 an important technology going forward.

469
00:55:15,720 --> 00:55:18,920
 Okay, we have one more question down there.

470
00:55:18,920 --> 00:55:21,880
 Yeah, Julia Wertz from the Austrian Central Bank.

471
00:55:22,760 --> 00:55:30,920
 So we've heard that competitiveness is a bit lacking in the EU and for various reasons and various ways to approach this.

472
00:55:30,920 --> 00:55:38,360
 But one aspect that we've also been alluded to by the opening remarks by Boris this morning is the role of subsidies.

473
00:55:38,360 --> 00:55:50,520
 I mean, he mentioned a very successful example here, this city of Ragusa where he said they always used in their high times subsidies to promote their local industry.

474
00:55:50,520 --> 00:56:02,200
 We have also been witnessing for decades now a very successful example, namely China, which has also heavily built on subsidizing its industries and the WTO could never get agreed on it.

475
00:56:02,200 --> 00:56:10,360
 So I wonder, is this probably the way to go and how would we go this way in Europe with our competition loss?

476
00:56:12,680 --> 00:56:13,960
 Well, that was a question for...

477
00:56:13,960 --> 00:56:18,680
 Well, I think at least Joe and Deborah can say something.

478
00:56:18,680 --> 00:56:19,160
 Okay.

479
00:56:19,160 --> 00:56:21,480
 I don't know.

480
00:56:21,480 --> 00:56:23,800
 Well, I'll start and then you can disagree.

481
00:56:23,800 --> 00:56:29,400
 Yeah, so subsidies certainly have to play a role here.

482
00:56:29,960 --> 00:56:43,640
 And I think the difficulties in designing a disincentive system, i.e. taxes and so on, are becoming clear that they're problematic.

483
00:56:43,640 --> 00:56:58,200
 And if we think about historical structural funds spending on things like highways and, you know, telecoms, you know, cables and so on,

484
00:56:58,760 --> 00:57:05,640
 maybe thinking not just in terms of subsidies individually to individual small agents, but about the basic infrastructure.

485
00:57:05,640 --> 00:57:08,840
 What do we need to put in, and there is discussion on this in Brussels, right?

486
00:57:08,840 --> 00:57:13,800
 So what do we need to put in place so that we can, we can in future transition, say, to hydrogen?

487
00:57:13,800 --> 00:57:21,960
 What do we need to put in place in terms of integrating the European grids so that we can generate wind or solar here and store it there?

488
00:57:23,160 --> 00:57:27,240
 And so I think we need to think big on subsidies, right?

489
00:57:27,240 --> 00:57:33,720
 So not specifically things to get individual firms changing, but what's the infrastructure that we need to support the transition?

490
00:57:33,720 --> 00:57:37,640
 That doesn't get into as much of a problem with competition policy, I think.

491
00:57:37,640 --> 00:57:40,440
 It does actually maybe avoid some of it.

492
00:57:40,440 --> 00:57:55,480
 So if you have national players involved in putting these new ways of moving power around of bringing in hydrogen and then perhaps taking advantage of existing gas systems and so on.

493
00:57:56,360 --> 00:58:06,040
 And so if we're in there from the beginning and it's not controlled by cartels that are, I mean, that I think maybe anticipates some of the problems we've had with the current, with the current system.

494
00:58:06,760 --> 00:58:10,040
 No, I'm all in on subsidies, but I think they need to be big.

495
00:58:10,040 --> 00:58:13,000
 We need to think in terms of a large-scale infrastructure.

496
00:58:13,000 --> 00:58:20,280
 I think it's a very difficult question.

497
00:58:20,280 --> 00:58:32,360
 So it's a very difficult question to say what's the right amount of subsidies and where do you place subsidy and what should be the rule of the public sector?

498
00:58:32,920 --> 00:58:40,120
 I think what we see coming out of the pandemic is a massive rule of the public sector and economy.

499
00:58:40,120 --> 00:58:48,520
 And I'm not sure as a, I don't know, I grew up as an economist thinking that the market works better than the public sector.

500
00:58:48,520 --> 00:58:52,280
 And now we have back the public sector supporting everything.

501
00:58:52,280 --> 00:58:58,920
 So my original, so my main point is maybe with the disclosure of where I come from,

502
00:59:00,280 --> 00:59:10,360
 I'm not in favor of massive subsidies, but subsidies can be important if very well targeted to address a certain market failure.

503
00:59:10,360 --> 00:59:17,480
 And in that case, I think it's important to have them if you really have the market failure and you address them.

504
00:59:17,480 --> 00:59:23,160
 I think it's very important that we have them at the European level and not at the national level.

505
00:59:23,640 --> 00:59:33,720
 And part of the exemption of stated rule brings to some countries, bring more subsidies to their own companies.

506
00:59:33,720 --> 00:59:36,840
 And that's distorts the market and the European single market.

507
00:59:36,840 --> 00:59:43,000
 And this, I think we should have a European instruments, at least looking in the medium to long term.

508
00:59:43,000 --> 00:59:50,600
 Crisis response is fine, but in the medium to long term, if we wanted to have the benefit of the single market,

509
00:59:50,600 --> 00:59:56,360
 we need to have a European instruments, particularly when we talk about subsidies.

510
00:59:56,360 --> 01:00:04,680
 And the other point that I have is that sometimes, and particularly in the concept of the net zero transition,

511
01:00:05,240 --> 01:00:11,320
 subsidies are needed because we have to compensate for other distortions that are in the market.

512
01:00:11,320 --> 01:00:20,200
 So maybe sometimes you have to also look at the source of the distortion that the subsidies need to compensate.

513
01:00:20,200 --> 01:00:30,440
 So a deep analysis of all the incentive system that we have and rules after rules that we have is important, I think.

514
01:00:30,440 --> 01:00:37,320
 I think we have maybe time for one more question from the audience, if there is any.

515
01:00:37,320 --> 01:00:47,720
 If not, maybe Mr. Florence, do we want to comment on potential subsidies in automotive industry?

516
01:00:47,720 --> 01:00:49,080
 Can it help?

517
01:00:49,080 --> 01:00:52,680
 Well, I'm just online with what has been said.

518
01:00:52,680 --> 01:01:02,120
 And if there is a lesson somewhere, it's just you don't have for one single problem, you don't have one single solution.

519
01:01:02,120 --> 01:01:09,640
 And you have to adapt yourself to what is really necessary, depending on your market, your location, and so on.

520
01:01:09,640 --> 01:01:12,840
 So, again, it's flexibility first.

521
01:01:13,800 --> 01:01:25,640
 This means, of course, innovation, protection of the intellectual property, which has been a strong weakness in

522
01:01:25,640 --> 01:01:30,040
 Europe in the past years, I think, and then education.

523
01:01:30,040 --> 01:01:40,120
 So that's the three key things that we have to consider if we want to be at the top in competition.

524
01:01:40,120 --> 01:01:44,840
 Mr. Francois, do you see the right direction in terms of education at the moment?

525
01:01:44,840 --> 01:01:50,840
 It varies by member state, and it varies by the associate states too, right?

526
01:01:50,840 --> 01:01:51,800
 Some yes, some no.

527
01:01:51,800 --> 01:02:01,640
 And, again, I think back to the Brexit example, right, with the UK dropping out of the Horizon program

528
01:02:02,280 --> 01:02:05,080
 and not finding a way to backstop that.

529
01:02:05,080 --> 01:02:09,960
 And so their role in sort of basic science research is put at risk, I think.

530
01:02:09,960 --> 01:02:17,560
 And it's clearly really important.

531
01:02:17,560 --> 01:02:22,120
 It's clear that I think more money is needed up front rather than less.

532
01:02:22,600 --> 01:02:29,000
 There is, I think, the move towards a bit more focus on European competitiveness is clear in the types

533
01:02:29,000 --> 01:02:32,120
 of central projects that are called for.

534
01:02:32,120 --> 01:02:38,760
 But we also need to think of how we incentivize firms to invest more in this R&D as well.

535
01:02:38,760 --> 01:02:46,200
 And I think some countries do better than others in terms of ensuring that the kind of people that are

536
01:02:46,200 --> 01:02:50,200
 are being -- the type of human capital that's being generated is what firms actually need.

537
01:02:50,200 --> 01:02:54,760
 It's a signal of some kind of disconnect if you see that there's tons of job openings that are

538
01:02:54,760 --> 01:02:55,880
 in certain areas of tech.

539
01:02:55,880 --> 01:02:58,200
 And then there's lots of people who can't find jobs because they don't match.

540
01:02:58,200 --> 01:03:05,000
 And so -- but, again, different countries have done better in Europe than others with that.

541
01:03:05,000 --> 01:03:08,360
 But in general, yeah, it's -- I agree entirely.

542
01:03:08,360 --> 01:03:09,880
 It's a key thing here.

543
01:03:09,880 --> 01:03:11,160
 It's where the innovation comes from.

544
01:03:11,160 --> 01:03:14,600
 It ensures that you can get the higher end on the supply chains.

545
01:03:14,600 --> 01:03:19,400
 It means that you're a better position, especially with IP protection, to generate the kinds

546
01:03:19,400 --> 01:03:24,440
 of innovations that then feed into these newer products.

547
01:03:24,440 --> 01:03:25,960
 Okay.

548
01:03:25,960 --> 01:03:31,160
 Madam Revoltella, some key points for conclusion from your side.

549
01:03:31,160 --> 01:03:38,840
 Well, I think I take back the point on skills.

